Creating a simple 2D fighting game like Tekken in a single HTML file requires embedding HTML, CSS, and JavaScript within the same document. Here is an extremely simplified version of a 2D fighting game with basic mechanics. Keep in mind that this is just a starting point and doesn't fully replicate the complexity of Tekken. It includes two players, basic movement, and health bars.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>2D Fighting Game</title>
  <style>
    body {
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      background-color: #1e1e1e;
      overflow: hidden;
    }
    canvas {
      display: block;
      margin: 0 auto;
      background-color: #000;
    }
    #healthBar1, #healthBar2 {
      position: fixed;
      top: 20px;
      width: 200px;
      height: 20px;
      background-color: red;
    }
    #healthBar1 {
      left: 20px;
    }
    #healthBar2 {
      right: 20px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <canvas id="gameCanvas"></canvas>
  <script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('gameCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
    canvas.width = 800;
    canvas.height = 400;

    const player1 = {
      x: 100,
      y: canvas.height - 150,
      width: 50,
      height: 100,
      color: 'blue',
      dx: 0,
      dy: 0,
      health: 100
    };

    const player2 = {
      x: canvas.width - 150,
      y: canvas.height - 150,
      width: 50,
      height: 100,
      color: 'red',
      dx: 0,
      dy: 0,
      health: 100
    };

    const gravity = 1;
    const friction = 0.9;

    let keys = {};

    document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      keys[e.code] = true;
    });

    document.addEventListener('keyup', (e) => {
      keys[e.code] = false;
    });

    function update() {
      player1.x += player1.dx;
      player1.y += player1.dy;

      player2.x += player2.dx;
      player2.y += player2.dy;

      // Player 1 Movement
      if (keys['ArrowLeft']) player1.dx = -5;
      else if (keys['ArrowRight']) player1.dx = 5;
      else player1.dx *= friction;

      if (keys['ArrowUp'] && player1.y === canvas.height - 150) player1.dy = -15;

      player1.dy += gravity;
      if (player1.y >= canvas.height - 150) player1.dy = 0;

      // Player 2 Movement
      if (keys['KeyA']) player2.dx = -5;
      else if (keys['KeyD']) player2.dx = 5;
      else player2.dx *= friction;

      if (keys['KeyW'] && player2.y === canvas.height - 150) player2.dy = -15;

      player2.dy += gravity;
      if (player2.y >= canvas.height - 150) player2.dy = 0;

      // Health Bar Update
      document.getElementById('healthBar1').style.width = player1.health + 'px';
      document.getElementById('healthBar2').style.width = player2.health + 'px';

      // Collision Detection (Punch)
      if (Math.abs(player1.x - player2.x) < player1.width && Math.abs(player1.y - player2.y) < player1.height) {
        if (keys['Space']) player2.health -= 1;
        if (keys['KeyH']) player1.health -= 1;
      }

      // Draw
      ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
      ctx.fillStyle = player1.color;
      ctx.fillRect(player1.x, player1.y, player1.width, player1.height);

      ctx.fillStyle = player2.color;
      ctx.fillRect(player2.x, player2.y, player2.width, player2.height);

      requestAnimationFrame(update);
    }

    update();
  </script>

  <div id="healthBar1"></div>
  <div id="healthBar2"></div>
</body>
</html>
```

### Breakdown:

- **HTML**: Defines the structure, including a `<canvas>` element where the game will be rendered.
- **CSS**: Styles the body and canvas, giving a dark background for the game area. Health bars are styled in fixed positions at the top left and top right.
- **JavaScript**:
  - Creates two player objects with basic attributes like position, health, and movement speed.
  - Player movement is controlled with arrow keys for player 1 and `A/D` for left/right and `W` for jump for player 2.
  - The game includes simple gravity for jumping.
  - Health bars decrease when players collide and "punch" each other (via space and `H` keys).
  - The game is constantly updated using `requestAnimationFrame` to keep the game loop running.

### Features:
- **Player Movement**: Left, right, and jumping for both players.
- **Health Bars**: Show each player's current health.
- **Collision Detection**: Basic collision between the players with health deduction when they "punch."
- **Game Loop**: Continuously updates the canvas to simulate movement and game mechanics.

This is a very basic starting point for a 2D fighting game. It can be expanded with more complex animations, special moves, sounds, and AI for an actual fight simulation!
